<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Sigh, the same old argument over and over again.<P>Can a mage root? only the target the pet is attacking.  Can a mage stun?  Only the target the pet is attacking.  Can a mage snare?  Nope.<P>The game is not a static one. It changes as you level.  Sure, for much of the game a mage is preferred.  This is the game when you are pulling single mobs, or camping a static spawn.  This is the game when you can handle most pulls simply by tanking through them, and when a mage really is almost two characters in one.<P>But just wait.  Wait until crowd control is required, and mismanagement of a pull will get the whole group wiped out.  At these levels, mages have a hard time finding groups.  My husband complains about the exact opposite of what you describe.  Groups tell him "you are just a low-rent wizard without ports" and "No, you can't use a pet.  He messes up the mez."<P>I just came down from three days in Hate.  We started with three mages, but one got disgruntled and left because he couldn't use his pet.  Pets were allowed TWICE--the two Maestro pulls.  Other than that, the mages were casting damage shields and getting 50% resists on nukes (after the Malosinini).<P>Now it looks like Velious will bring back the desireability of mages somewhat.  When mobs have 500,000 health it is nice to have lots of disposable tanks that don't need heals and never get tired.<P>But don't think that mages are always more desired than wizards.<BR><P>------------------<BR>Quesci Jinete, 53 Wizard<BR>Quescient Sera, 48 Monk<BR>Wings of Wrath<BR>Wife of Damascis Apocalypse (Quellious)<BR>"Do not meddle in the affairs of Wizards, for they are subtle, and quick to anger"
</FONT>
